ctivities, in particular their bequests and benefactions, theirinvolvement in the affairs of their houses, and their burials in the conventual churches; and it argues that the ties which bound the two parties together, whether amicable, indifferent or abusive, continued right up until the Dissolution brought monastic life in England and Wales to an end. KAREN STÖBER is a Lecturer in Medieval History at the University of Aberystwyth  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMonasteriesxEnglandxHistory. 0aMonasteriesxWalesxHistory. 0aMonasterieszEnglandxHistory. 0aMonasterieszWalesxHistory. 0aMonastic and religious lifexEnglandxHistory, Middle Ages, 600-1500. 0aMonastic and religious lifexWalesxHistory, Middle Ages, 600-1500. 0aMonastic and religious lifezEnglandxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aMonastic and religious lifezWalesxHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aPatronage, EcclesiasticalxEnglandxHistory. 0aPatronage, EcclesiasticalxWalesxHistory. 0aPatronage, EcclesiasticalzEnglandxHistory. 0aPatronage, EcclesiasticalzWalesxHistory. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781846155628?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846155628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846155628/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles